# Supabase Database Patterns

## Schema Conventions

- All PKs are `uuid` with `DEFAULT gen_random_uuid()` (except `profiles.id` which mirrors `auth.users.id`)
- All tables have `created_at timestamptz DEFAULT now()`
- Mutable tables have `updated_at timestamptz` with an `update_updated_at()` trigger
- Use Postgres enums for finite value sets: `user_role`, `execution_status`, `automation_status`, `platform`, `test_case_type`, `test_run_status`, `invitation_status`, `webhook_event_status`, `import_status`
- Cascade deletes: child tables use `ON DELETE CASCADE` (steps, execution_results, annotations, attachments, versions, import_errors)
- Referential tables use `ON DELETE SET NULL` (assignee_id, suite_id on test_runs)

## Supabase Client

- Use `@supabase/supabase-js` with typed client generated from the schema
- Server components and API routes: use `createServerClient` from `@supabase/ssr`
- Client components: use `createBrowserClient` from `@supabase/ssr`
- Never expose `service_role` key to the client — use it only in API routes/Edge Functions for webhook processing
- Always call `supabase.auth.getUser()` (not `getSession()`) for server-side auth checks

## Query Patterns

- Always scope queries to authenticated user context — the RLS policies enforce access
- Use `.select()` with explicit column lists and join syntax for related data
- For test case ID generation, use the `generate_test_case_id(suite_id)` Postgres function — never generate IDs client-side
- Batch operations (bulk edit, CSV import) should use Postgres transactions via `supabase.rpc()`
- Use `supabase.storage` for screenshot uploads — bucket path: `screenshots/{project_id}/{test_run_id}/{annotation_id}_{filename}`

## Full Schema Reference

See `docs/schema.md` for complete table definitions, constraints, indexes, and RLS policies. Always verify column names and types against this document before writing queries.
